The two Poland
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
Former Solidarity leader, former political prisoner and former foreign minister - who led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another declaration saying he was not a secret police agent at the time of communism.
European parliamentarians talked of a "witch hunt" regarding the Polish government's conduct and Geremek said that the law on lustration constitutes a threat to public liberties.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and stirring up anti-Polish sentiment.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A constitutional court ruling dated May 11 has largely invalidated the lustration law, allowing Geremek to keep his seat in the European Parliament at least for now.
However, this law is part of a general policy of the Polish government that has no other purpose than to weaken the country's institutions and its democratic fabric.
What's happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began ?
Each revolution passes through two phases: first a fight for freedom, then a struggle for power.
The first is an emancipation of the human soul by which man expresses what is best in him, while the second frees the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and a desire for vengeance.
The revolution triggered by the Polish trade union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into hiding when martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to resurface in 1989, in the wake of Gorbachev's "perestroika".
During the negotiations that brought an end to the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship across the entire Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a reconciliatory attitude rather than one of vengeance, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a divided country between the all-powerful winners and the oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and a market economy.
Not everyone followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revenge-seekers, post-communist provincial troublemakers, xenophobic and anti-Semitic groups, heirs of pre-war chauvinism, and the circles around Radio Maryja, a mouthpiece of ethnic-clerical fundamentalism.
Alarming signs are visible everywhere: the authority of the Justice is undermined, the independence of the constitutional court is being questioned, officials are being bought and the office of the prosecutor is politicized.
Every day, social life undergoes repressive regulation.
What's all this about?
Each successful revolution has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought public freedoms, but also more crime, a market economy, as well as the risks of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, and the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a growing income gap.
She opened Poland to Europe, but she also induced the fear of the stranger and the fear of a massive invasion of Western culture.
For the losers of the Polish revolution of 1989, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainty.
In large corporations, Solidarity workers have become the victims of the freedoms they have conquered.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered to belong to the state, but the latter took care of them.
In a world of freedom, no one is there to take care of us.
It's in this atmosphere of anxiety that the current coalition governs, combining George Bush's conservative potion with Vladimir Putin's centralism.
Solidarity veterans believed that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the firmament.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished and the virtuous militants of Solidarity were not rewarded.
Also, the feeling of injustice has given birth to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed at both old enemies and old friends who seemed to be getting away with it.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was Poland's greatest achievement in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland lacked a moral revolution that would make crimes unpunished, virtue unrewarded and injustices uncorrected.
After their defeat in the 2005 general elections, the losing parties chose a method: a large-scale purge.
According to initial estimates, lustration should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the security services' archives; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people promised de-lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be fired and barred from practicing their profession for ten years.
