Cardinal Dziwisz of Krakow reminds us that there is no place for "revenge, vengeance, lack of respect for human dignity and unfounded accusations."
Never since the fall of communism, a cardinal has used words as strong.
Should this cleansing have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The goal of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspects, proven or not, of having belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither Leszek Balcerowicz's economic reforms nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would be neither a member of NATO, nor the European Union.
Today, two Poles face each other.
Poland of suspicion, fear, and vengeance fights Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland, made of openness and tolerance, that of John Paul II and Czeslaw Milosz, of my friends from the underground and from prison, must prevail.
I believe the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The constitutional court's decision leaves hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will neither destroy what gave birth to it, the will to freedom, nor what it has produced, a democratic state.
